{"id":14881710,"mediaExerciseId":"3b93a129-0889-4cc3-ab35-d846035c4449","exerciseName":"8","chapterName":"20","chapterTitle":"Credit and Inventory Management","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"20.8","sectionTitle":"Inventory Management Techniques","pageNumber":697,"solutions":[{"id":6041338,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we need to explain what the EOQ determines for the company, and to list the cost component of the EOQ model that is affected and minimized by the JIP inventory system. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"**a)** The economic order quantity  EOQ model is the best known model for explicitly establishing optimal inventory levels. This model analyzes the level of inventory that a firm must have at a given time. In other words, it analyzes how many orders a firm needs to execute to replenish its inventory. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**b)**  Just-in-time, or JIT inventory is a modern approach to dependent inventory management whose primary goal is to keep those inventories to a minimum. Therefore, the basic goal of this system is that the firm has enough inventory at hand to meet the current needs of production, not to accumulate inventory more than what is needed for production. Such a system requires continuous and constant renewal of inventory in accordance with the production plan. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"28cb7ca6-808b-4daa-9eb5-c67be1c5a10f","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","image